This document covers the network infrastructure discovery capabilities within OWASP Amass, focusing on network mapping, ASN discovery, WHOIS integration, and HTTP-based service detection. These components work together to map network relationships and discover services running on discovered IP addresses.

## 1. Network Mapping and ASN Discovery

Amass discovers network infrastructure relationships by mapping IP addresses to their containing network blocks and associated Autonomous Systems (ASNs). This process leverages multiple data sources including BGP routing information and WHOIS records.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    subgraph "Network Discovery Pipeline"
        IPAddress["IPAddress Asset"] --> ipNetblock["ip_netblock plugin"]
        ipNetblock --> IPNetblock["IPNetblock.lookup()"]
        IPNetblock --> CIDRRanger["session.CIDRanger()"]
        
        IPAddress --> bgpTools["bgptools plugin"]
        bgpTools --> netblockHandler["netblock handler"]
        netblockHandler --> bgpWhois["bgpTools.whois()"]
        bgpWhois --> bgpToolsRecord["bgpToolsRecord"]
        
        bgpToolsRecord --> NetblockAsset["Netblock Asset"]
        bgpToolsRecord --> ASNAsset["AutonomousSystem Asset"]
        
        NetblockAsset --> autsysHandler["autsys handler"]
        autsysHandler --> ASNAsset
        
        IPNetblock --> ReservedCheck["amassnet.IsReservedAddress()"]
        ReservedCheck --> ReservedAS["Reserved AS0 handling"]
    end
```

The network mapping process follows this flow:
1. IP addresses trigger the `ip_netblock` plugin for initial netblock discovery
2. BGP Tools plugin performs WHOIS queries to `bgp.tools` for authoritative network information
3. Discovered netblocks trigger autonomous system discovery
4. All relationships are stored in the session's `CIDRanger` for efficient lookups

Sources: [engine/plugins/ip_netblock.go:70-112](), [engine/plugins/whois/bgptools/netblock.go:33-72](), [engine/plugins/whois/bgptools/autsys.go:35-59]()

### 1.1 IP Address to Netblock Mapping

The `ip_netblock` plugin handles the core logic for mapping IP addresses to their containing network blocks. This process checks for existing netblock associations and creates new ones when necessary.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    subgraph "IP to Netblock Mapping Process"
        IPAsset["IPAddress Asset"] --> ReservedCheck["amassnet.IsReservedAddress()"]
        ReservedCheck -->|true| ReservedHandler["reservedAS() handling"]
        ReservedCheck -->|false| CIDRLookup["support.IPNetblock()"]
        
        CIDRLookup --> CIDRangerEntry["sessions.CIDRangerEntry"]
        CIDRangerEntry --> NetblockCreation["Create Netblock Asset"]
        CIDRangerEntry --> ASNCreation["Create AutonomousSystem Asset"]
        
        NetblockCreation --> ContainsEdge["'contains' relationship"]
        ASNCreation --> AnnouncesEdge["'announces' relationship"]
        
        ReservedHandler --> ReservedNetblock["Reserved Netblock (AS0)"]
        ReservedHandler --> AutnumRecord["AutnumRecord Asset"]
    end
```

Reserved IP addresses are handled specially by creating a netblock with ASN 0 and an associated `AutnumRecord` with the name "Reserved Network Address Blocks".

