This guide provides comprehensive information for developers who want to contribute to or extend the OWASP Amass project. It covers setting up a development environment, understanding the build and release processes, working with the test framework, and contributing code to the project. For information about using Amass as an end-user, please refer to the [Command Line Interface](#2) and [Configuration](#3) pages.

## Development Environment Setup

To begin developing for Amass, you'll need to set up your local environment with the necessary tools and dependencies.

### Prerequisites

- **Go**: Amass requires Go 1.19 or later
- **Git**: For source control management
- **Docker** (optional): For container-based development and testing

### Getting the Source Code

```bash
# Clone the repository
git clone https://github.com/owasp-amass/amass.git
cd amass

# Download dependencies
go mod download
```

### Project Structure

Amass follows a standard Go project layout with the following key directories:

| Directory | Purpose |
|-----------|---------|
| `/cmd` | Application entry points |
| `/format` | Output formatting functionality |
| `/resources` | Static resources used by the application |
| `/examples` | Example configurations for reference |
| `.github/workflows` | CI/CD pipeline definitions |

Sources: [go.mod:1-95](), [README.md:1-135]()

## Build System

Amass uses a sophisticated build system to create binaries for multiple platforms and package them for distribution.

### Building Locally

For local development, you can build Amass using Go's standard build tools:

```bash
# Build the main binary
go build -o amass ./cmd/amass

# Install to your GOPATH
go install -v github.com/owasp-amass/amass/v4/...@master
```

### Build and Release Process

Amass uses GoReleaser to automate the creation of releases. The process is triggered when a new tag is pushed to the repository.

